---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeTabs from '../../../components/CodeTabs.astro';

const create = `import { createField } from 'forces-ui';

const canvas = document.querySelector('canvas');
const field = createField(canvas, {
  accent: '#4da3ff',
  density: 1,
  attention: false,
  causality: false,
});

// the field reads every [data-body] element on the page.
// after you add or remove bodies, rescan:
field.scan();`;

const custom = `import { createField } from 'forces-ui';

// a custom force is just an object with token + apply(b, p, env).
// register it on a fresh field by composing your own — or use the catalog.
// (advanced) see the Force type in the types reference.`;
---

<DocsLayout
  title="forces-ui — Core engine guide"
  description="Drive the forces-ui engine directly: createField() on a canvas you own, returning the FieldHandle. Zero runtime dependencies. For a managed canvas and a typed class, see the TypeScript guide."
>
  <header class="docs-hero">
    <p class="kicker">Guides</p>
    <h1>The <span class="accent">core engine</span></h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Skip every wrapper and drive the engine on a canvas you own. The core is zero-dependency
      TypeScript. For a managed canvas and an ergonomic class, reach for the
      <a href="/docs/guides/typescript">TypeScript wrapper</a> instead.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <div class="pkg">
      <code class="install" data-copy="npm i forces-ui">npm i forces-ui</code>
      <span>the engine itself — when you own the canvas</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>createField — your own canvas</h2>
    <p>
      When you want to place and size the canvas yourself, hand it to <code>createField</code>.
      You get the <a href="/docs/api/handle">FieldHandle</a>. This is the lowest-level entry
      point; the web component, the React adapter, and <code>@forces-ui/vanilla</code> all wrap it.
    </p>
    <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'TypeScript', lang: 'ts', code: create }]} />
    <div class="callout">
      <b>The canvas is decorative.</b> Position it fixed behind your content
      (<code>position: fixed; inset: 0; z-index: 0; pointer-events: none</code>) and mark it
      <code>aria-hidden</code>. Reduced motion is honoured automatically, and the loop pauses
      when the tab is backgrounded.
    </div>
    <div class="callout">
      <b>Want a managed canvas?</b> <code>@forces-ui/vanilla</code> creates and tears down the
      canvas for you — as a <code>ForcesField</code> class or the <code>mountField()</code>
      function. See the <a href="/docs/guides/typescript">TypeScript guide</a>.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Custom forces</h2>
    <p>
      A force is just <code>{'{ token, apply(b, p, env) }'}</code>. The engine never special-cases
      any single force — they all implement the same contract, so you can author your own against
      the <a href="/docs/api/types">Force type</a>.
    </p>
    <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'TypeScript', lang: 'ts', code: custom }]} />
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
